ral worlds of the Venetian heretics—those men and women who articulated their hopes for religious and political reform and whose ideologies ranged from evangelical to anabaptist and even millenarian positions. In exploring the connections between religious beliefs and social experience, he weaves a rich tapestry of Renaissance urban life that is sure to intrigue all those involved in anthropological, religious, and historical studies—students and scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian heresiesxHistoryx16th centuryxItalyxVenice. 0aChristian heresieszItalyzVenicexHistoryy16th century. 0aReformationxItalyxVenice. 0aReformationzItalyzVenice. 0aRenaissancexItalyxVenice. 0aRenaissancezItalyzVenice. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aancient cities.  aanthropological studies.  acatholicism.  acultural history.  ahistorical changes.  ahistorical city.  ahistorical studies.  ahistory early modern.  ahistory italy.  ainnovative approach.  aitalian cities.  apolitcal freedom.  apolitical freedom.  areligion.  areligious crisis.  areligious dissent.  areligious history.  areligious nonconformists.  arenaissance cities.  asocially harmonious city.  astudents and scholars.  aurban life.  avenetian heretics.  avenetian studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007743040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520912335?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912335/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles